Notes for Practical
Control + shift + p opens command prompt
cd stands for change directory
To change straight to the home directory from a deeper one, use cd $HOME, cd ~, or cd ../ (repeat as many times as needed)
pwd means print working directory
ls means list and shows everything in the directory
Control + C cancels what is currently being typed
Clear clears the terminal
ls has different options; ls -F shows files, ls -lrth shows a bunch of information about directories
man means manual and typing a command after that explains it
Tab autofills commands
* is the wildcard
ls -a shows hidden directories
print out the bottom of something by using the command tail (file name)
Can use file contents with less, cat, head, or tail
Commands cp, mv, and mkdir are useful for manipulating existing files and creating new directories
Use mkdir -p to create multiple files at once
History command and then up arrows shows previous commands
Doing ls -laF gives the (l) long format, (a) all of it, (F) and the format
grep looks through a file and the first thing you put after grep is what you are searching for (might want to use quotes)
less looks through files and lets you scroll through it rather than printing it across the whole screen
used ls -lh to find the size of the file in human readable format
chmod means change mode
conda activate genomics activates genomics
conda deactivate deactivates it
using less -S keeps everything that is on one line on it
> is a redirect, goes to the place you want
>> is the append, it does the same thing but it doubles it
doing -v does the inverse of grep and removes all the matches from the output
doing ^ in front of a special character when doing a grep searches for it at the front
man goes to the manual
which will find were something is installed
unzip unzips zip-compressed files; gunzip does the same for gzip-compressed files
grep -c ‘example’ will search for the number of times the searched for term appears
rm removes things